<font color="#FF0000">GRANDFATHERS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug  9 16:18:56 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Humming Eagle,<br><br>
Your grandfathers' way of dealing with the enemy *was* completely practical and correct within the context of their belief structure and view of their connection with life. They were consistent, honest, and completely above board. Everyone played by the same rules, and you knew the score. They commanded respect. They have mine. They have honor. They still live, so to speak.<br><br>
I find it far more desireable to be killed and eaten by a lion whose motives are truly honest, than being the victim of lesser circumstances.<br><br>
A thousand years ago, my direct ancestors embellished their shields with the skins of European blue squrrels as they went into battle in Italy and around Rome. This was their sign of honor, identification, and unity. I am still learning about them, but what I may uncover I am sure will not surprise me.<br><br>
I have come to realize that context is everything, and much of that which we perceive as &quot;right or &quot;wrong&quot; is strongly dependent upon our point of view. The lion, whose motives are &quot;right&quot; because he is just hungry or defending his turf, regardless that I may not like what he is about to do, has honor, and that must be respected. There are those, however, who would see lions eradicated for the honest expression of the lions' context and natural way. It is with these individuals that I have trouble understanding. Is it perhaps there is nothing there to understand? I wonder. Some of it makes no sense, unless we introduce evil. That is altogether another story.<br><br>
It is within this context of image, connection, and honor that I am beginning to process some of my Vietnam War legacy, the gift that keeps on giving. I find it difficult for me to start mid way and proceed. I must return to the very beginning, the human base of it all, and then move ahead. There are Tunkasila everywhere, and I am beginning to find them and listen to what they have to say. It still hurts real bad at times. That, I am afraid, is a very normal part of it all. It will be with me always. <br><br>
Hecito yelo, Brother. <br><br>
       
